{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DUTZKm46uejaqz9AQUqD61","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 18 — Failure Analysis\n     2→\n     3→## Overview\n     4→\n     5→54 failures out of 203 test cases (73% pass rate). The failures cluster into 8 distinct root-cause patterns. Most failures involve one of two dominant issues: **ALL_CAPS vs. Title Case mismatch** (algorithm faithfully returns OCR casing but test expects canonical mixed case) and **OCR garbage prologue that bypasses burst detection** (long garbage lines sneak through and beat the real title). Several other structural bugs account for the remainder.\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## Pattern 1: ALL_CAPS Title in OCR, Mixed-Case Expected (largest group, ~20 failures)\n    10→\n    11→**Affected files:** Barszcz, Beef Stew, Mushroom Pasta, Mushroom Barley Soup, Kluski Śląskie, Pierogi Ruskie, Placki Serowe, Placki Ziemniaczane, Placki Owocowe, Placki Słodkie, Roladki Szpinakowe, Paella Valenciana, Chocolate Brownies + Fudgy Chocolate Brownies, and others.\n    12→\n    13→**What the OCR has:** The recipe title is in ALL_CAPS (e.g., `BARSZCZ`, `BEEF STEW`, `MUSHROOM PASTA`, `PLACKI SEROWE`).\n    14→\n    15→**What the algorithm returns:** The verbatim OCR string in ALL_CAPS (e.g., `BARSZCZ`, `BEEF STEW`).\n    16→\n    17→**What the test expects:** Title-cased string (e.g., `Barszcz`, `Beef Stew`, `Placki Serowe`).\n    18→\n    19→**Why it fails:** The algorithm has no case normalization step. It returns text exactly as it appears in the OCR. Tests that have ALL_CAPS expectations (e.g., `KREM SELEROWY Z GORGONZOLA`, `ARAYES SHRAK`) pass because the expected string matches the OCR. Tests with Title Case expectations fail because the expected string differs in case.\n    20→\n    21→**Concrete trace — Barszcz:**\n    22→```\n    23→File line 1: BARSZCZ\n    24→Expected:    Barszcz\n    25→Got:         BARSZCZ\n    26→```\n    27→`BARSZCZ` is a valid single-word structural candidate. It passes all hard filters and scores well for recipe title. The algorithm returns it faithfully. The test fails on a string-equality comparison.\n    28→\n    29→**Concrete trace — Paella Valenciana:**\n    30→```\n    31→File line 1: PAELLA\n    32→File line 2: VALENCIANA\n    33→```\n    34→Both are ALL_CAPS single-word lines (≤2 words, ≤25 chars). The caps-coalescing logic correctly merges them into `PAELLA VALENCIANA`. But expected is `Paella Valenciana`. Case mismatch.\n    35→\n    36→---\n    37→\n    38→## Pattern 2: Polish Preposition `ze` Triggers Garbled-Word False Positive\n    39→\n    40→**Affected files:** Krem Grzybowy ze Śmietaną, Konfitury ze Liwek.\n    41→\n    42→**Why it fails:** The `isLikelyGarbled` multi-word check flags any short (≤2 letter) lowercase word that is not in `commonShort2`. The set `commonShort2` contains `\"z\"` (common Polish preposition) but NOT `\"ze\"` (its form used before consonant clusters). The title `Krem Grzybowy ze Śmietaną` contains `ze`, which:\n    43→- starts with lowercase `z` → `/^[a-z]/` matches\n    44→- `\"ze\".replace(/[^a-z]/g, \"\")` = `\"ze\"`, length 2 ≤ 2\n    45→- `\"ze\"` is not in `commonShort2`\n    46→\n    47→So `isLikelyGarbled(\"Krem Grzybowy ze Śmietaną\")` returns `true`, and `passesHardFilters` returns `false`. The actual title is entirely absent from the candidate pool. The algorithm picks something else (likely a body-text or ingredient line).\n    48→\n    49→**Concrete trace — Krem Grzybowy ze Śmietaną:**\n    50→```\n    51→File line 1: Krem Grzybowy ze Śmietaną   ← filtered out; ze not in commonShort2\n    52→File line 8: Składniki (4-5 porcji)      ← survives, becomes best candidate\n    53→```\n    54→\n    55→---\n    56→\n    57→## Pattern 3: Two-Word Title Split Across Lines — Dedup Removes the Compound\n    58→\n    59→**Affected files:** Lamb Stew, Żur Żytni, and likely others.\n    60→\n    61→**Why it fails:** When a two-word title is split across two lines, each word becomes both a valid single-line candidate AND part of a 2-line join candidate. The dedup logic (\"keep the shorter substring\") then removes the compound join.\n    62→\n    63→**Concrete trace — Lamb Stew:**\n    64→```\n    65→File line 1: Lamb     ← single candidate: passes (4 ASCII letters, vowel ratio OK)\n    66→File line 2: Stew     ← single candidate: passes (4 ASCII letters, vowel ratio OK)\n    67→2-line join: Lamb Stew ← also generated\n    68→```\n    69→All three pass threshold. Dedup runs:\n    70→- `Lamb Stew` contains `Lamb` (shorter) → `Lamb Stew` removed\n    71→- `Lamb Stew` contains `Stew` (shorter) → `Lamb Stew` removed\n    72→- Result: `Lamb` and `Stew` survive → returns `Lamb + Stew`\n    73→\n    74→Expected `Lamb Stew`. The compound title is destroyed by its own component parts.\n    75→\n    76→**Concrete trace — Żur Żytni:**\n    77→```\n    78→File line 1: Żur     ← isLikelyGarbled (Ż is non-ASCII, ASCII letters = \"ur\" = 2 chars, triggers single-word short rule)\n    79→File line 2: żytni   ← single candidate\n    80→2-line join: Żur żytni  ← generated with lowercase ż\n    81→Expected:    Żur Żytni   ← Title Case mismatch AND the join is case-wrong\n    82→```\n    83→Additionally, `Żur` alone (ASCII letters = `ur`, 2 chars, not in COMMON_SHORT) is filtered as garbled. The 2-line join `Żur żytni` survives but has wrong casing on the second word, so even if returned it doesn't match.\n    84→\n    85→---\n    86→\n    87→## Pattern 4: Three-Line Title Where First Word Is a SECTION_LABEL\n    88→\n    89→**Affected files:** Zupy Zimowe Warzywne.\n    90→\n    91→**What the OCR has:**\n    92→```\n    93→Zupy\n    94→Zimowe\n    95→Warzywne\n    96→```\n    97→\n    98→**Why it fails:** `Zupy` appears in `SECTION_LABELS` (as a Polish category word meaning \"soups\"). The `buildCandidates` function skips 2-line and 3-line joins when the first line is a section label:\n    99→\n   100→```typescript\n   101→if (i + 1 < mergedLines.length && !isSectionLabel(line.text)) {\n   102→    // 2-line join only generated if first line is NOT a section label\n   103→```\n   104→\n   105→Since `isSectionLabel(\"Zupy\")` returns `true`, no join starting with `Zupy` is ever generated. The only surviving candidates are `Zimowe` (a single word, unusual English/Polish mix) and `Warzywne` (a single word). Neither matches the expected `Zupy Zimowe Warzywne`.\n   106→\n   107→The SECTION_LABELS entry is correct when `Zupy` appears as a standalone chapter header — but it incorrectly blocks reconstruction when `Zupy` is the start of a recipe title split across lines.\n   108→\n   109→---\n   110→\n   111→## Pattern 5: Long OCR Garbage Prologue Bypasses Burst Detection\n   112→\n   113→**Affected files:** Brownies, Sernik, Szarlotka, Zupa Grzybowa, Lemonade, Strawberry Shortcake, Strawberry Smoothie, Tomato Bisque, Tomato Chutney, Vegetable Stir Fry, Quick Golabki, and others.\n   114→\n   115→**Template structure:** These files start with ~28-35 lines of repeated OCR garbage instruction fragments (e.g., `½ cup plus ı tablespoon of finely ground`, `nto a loured work counter and knead until smooth`, `Beat egg whites until stiff peaks form, then fold`), followed by the actual recipe name as a simple mixed-case word, then a generic template recipe body.\n   116→\n   117→**Why it fails:** `findBurstEnd` only skips lines that are BOTH short (< 20 chars) AND garbled. The garbage lines in these files are long (30–55 chars), so `findBurstEnd` returns 0 and all lines are processed.\n   118→\n   119→Several garbage lines pass `passesHardFilters`:\n   120→- `Beat egg whites until stiff peaks form, then fold` — starts with uppercase `B`, no period-space pattern, all short lowercase words exceed 2 chars → passes\n   121→- `Cool completely on a wire rack before serving` — same\n   122→- `Remove from heat and stir in the cream` — same\n   123→\n   124→These become candidates. The actual title (`Szarlotka`, `Sernik`, etc.) is at ~70% through the document, gets no position bonus, and is a single uncommon Polish word. These competing candidates inflate the scoring pool and may push the real title below threshold or cause a wrong winner.\n   125→\n   126→**Concrete trace — Szarlotka:**\n   127→```\n   128→Lines 1–35:  OCR garbage (long lines, mostly pass filters)\n   129→Line 36:     Szarlotka   ← at 70% of document, no position bonus\n   130→Lines 38–56: Generic template ingredients/instructions\n   131→```\n   132→The algorithm has 20+ candidates before the title and must identify `Szarlotka` from among generic English cooking instructions. If the threshold is set by any garbage line with accidentally high embedding similarity to a recipe title, `Szarlotka` may not survive.\n   133→\n   134→---\n   135→\n   136→## Pattern 6: Season/Context Header Wins Over Mixed-Case Title\n   137→\n   138→**Affected files:** Beet Salad, Coleslaw, and similar files with `SEZON: WIOSNA` header.\n   139→\n   140→**Structure:**\n   141→```\n   142→SEZON: WIOSNA   ← line 1, ALL_CAPS, passes hard filters\n   143→[blank]\n   144→Beet Salad      ← line 3, mixed case\n   145→```\n   146→\n   147→**Why it fails:** `SEZON: WIOSNA` passes hard filters and `isStructuralHeading` check (ALL_CAPS, 2 words, both ≥4 letters). It gets a 0.10 structural bonus AND a 0.12 position bonus (position 0). `Beet Salad` at position 2 gets a smaller position bonus and no structural bonus. The algorithm picks `SEZON: WIOSNA`.\n   148→\n   149→The `METADATA_PATTERNS` list handles `DLA`, `SERVES`, `PREP TIME`, etc. but does not include `SEZON:` (season indicator). Seasonal recipe categorization headers like `SEZON: WIOSNA`, `SEZON: JESIEŃ` are not recognized as metadata.\n   150→\n   151→---\n   152→\n   153→## Pattern 7: Parenthetical English Subtitles Over-Merged Into Title\n   154→\n   155→**Affected files:** Piernik, Żurek, Pierogi Ruskie, Bigos Myśliwski, Makowiec.\n   156→\n   157→**What the OCR has:**\n   158→```\n   159→PIEROGI RUSKIE\n   160→(Boiled Dumplings with Potato and Cheese)\n   161→```\n   162→or:\n   163→```\n   164→MAKOWIEC (Polish Poppy Seed Cake)   ← already on one line\n   165→```\n   166→\n   167→**Why it fails:** The continuation pre-merge step merges any line starting with `(` into the preceding line (designed for `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`). This incorrectly merges English subtitle glosses.\n   168→\n   169→Result: `PIEROGI RUSKIE (Boiled Dumplings with Potato and Cheese)` becomes the candidate instead of `PIEROGI RUSKIE`. The expected is `Pierogi Ruskie`. Two problems: ALL_CAPS mismatch AND parenthetical inclusion.\n   170→\n   171→For single-line cases (`MAKOWIEC (Polish Poppy Seed Cake)`), `isAllCaps` returns `false` (the parenthetical content is mixed case), so the line doesn't qualify as a structural heading, and the full string including the gloss is returned as a mixed-case title — while `Makowiec` alone is expected.\n   172→\n   173→---\n   174→\n   175→## Pattern 8: Compound Title Destroyed by Dedup via Substring\n   176→\n   177→**Affected file:** HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION.\n   178→\n   179→**Structure:**\n   180→```\n   181→HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION  ← line 1 (compound title)\n   182→[blank]\n   183→HERB BAKED SALMON                          ← line 3 (first sub-recipe header)\n   184→...\n   185→DILL SAUCE VARIATION                       ← line 32 (second sub-recipe header)\n   186→```\n   187→\n   188→**Why it fails:** `HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION` at line 1 is the correct answer. All three ALL_CAPS candidates survive threshold. The continuation logic correctly identifies `HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION` as `firstStructuralHeading`. The prefix-removal step correctly removes `HERB BAKED SALMON`. However, `DILL SAUCE VARIATION` (position 32) also survives.\n   189→\n   190→Dedup then runs on `[HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION, DILL SAUCE VARIATION]`:\n   191→- `HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION` **contains** `DILL SAUCE VARIATION` (shorter)\n   192→- → The longer compound title is removed; only `DILL SAUCE VARIATION` survives\n   193→\n   194→The dedup rule \"keep the shorter\" is correct in general but breaks when the compound line-1 title literally contains a later sub-recipe section header as a substring.\n   195→\n   196→---\n   197→\n   198→## Minor Patterns\n   199→\n   200→### Pattern 9: Page Number Prefix Blocks Title Line\n   201→**File:** Berry Jam.\n   202→\n   203→OCR line 3: `34  Berry Jam`. The `startsWithNumber` check matches (line begins with digit `3`). The entire line is discarded. `Berry Jam` never appears as a standalone candidate.\n   204→\n   205→### Pattern 10: OCR Character Substitution in Title\n   206→**File:** Crème Brûlée.\n   207→\n   208→OCR line 1: `Crème Brû1ée` (digit `1` substituted for letter `l`). The algorithm returns the corrupted OCR string. Expected: `Crème Brûlée`. The algorithm does no character-substitution correction.\n   209→\n   210→### Pattern 11: Missing Word in OCR Split Title\n   211→**File:** Bigos z Wdzonych Kielbas.\n   212→\n   213→OCR: `Bigos` (line 1) + `Wdzonych Kielbas` (line 2). The preposition `z` is absent from the OCR. The 2-line join produces `Bigos Wdzonych Kielbas`. Expected: `Bigos z Wdzonych Kielbas`. An OCR omission that cannot be recovered without external knowledge.\n   214→\n   215→---\n   216→\n   217→## Common Themes\n   218→\n   219→### 1. No case normalization\n   220→The algorithm treats OCR casing as ground truth. Roughly a third of failures are pure ALL_CAPS vs. Title Case mismatches where the algorithm found the right title content but returned it in the wrong case. Adding a normalization pass (e.g., Title Case for mixed-alpha strings, preserve ALL_CAPS only when all non-trivial words are ≥5 chars or it's a known-ALL-CAPS pattern) would eliminate the largest single failure cluster.\n   221→\n   222→### 2. The garbled-word filter is too aggressive for non-ASCII short words\n   223→`ze`, and potentially other valid 2-letter tokens in languages with non-ASCII characters, are treated as garbage because the `commonShort2` set is ASCII-English-centric and the `[a-z]` regex only matches ASCII. Words like `ze`, `bo`, `ni`, `tu` are legitimate Polish words/prepositions but all fail the filter. The fix is to add Polish short prepositions to `commonShort2` (at minimum: `ze`, `bo`, `na`, `ni`, `po`, `ku`).\n   224→\n   225→### 3. The burst-detection threshold (< 20 chars) is too narrow\n   226→Long repeated OCR garbage lines bypass `findBurstEnd` because they exceed 20 characters. The burst detection should also recognize long repeated lines (appearing ≥2 times before the first likely title candidate) as garbage preamble. Alternatively, a repeated-line filter (any line appearing ≥3 times in the document is noise) would handle these template-garbage files.\n   227→\n   228→### 4. The \"shorter wins\" dedup rule and the \"section labels block joins\" rule each have known exceptions\n   229→- The dedup rule breaks when a compound title on line 1 contains a later sub-recipe header as a literal substring (HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION).\n   230→- The section-label join-block rule breaks when a category word (`Zupy`, potentially `Placki`) starts a multi-line recipe title rather than standing alone as a category.\n   231→\n   232→These two rules are already annotated in the code as sensitive (\"DO NOT CHANGE THIS LOGIC\"), so any fix should be targeted rather than broad.\n   233→\n   234→### 5. Continuation pre-merge is too aggressive with `(`\n   235→The `(` continuation character is designed for recipe variant suffixes like `(VARIATION D)`. It also matches English subtitle glosses like `(Polish Gingerbread)` and `(Hunter's Stew)`. A simple guard — don't merge `(` continuations when the preceding line is already a complete multi-word title — would prevent most cases in Pattern 7.\n   236→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01XdvAmX8uYeobcBc1WPNrCk","session_id":"8b8858bc-a11e-49e9-aee6-802d54bbaef0","uuid":"7f96bce1-b6fe-4020-a788-92dd4babc178"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0171Wt55MTRV4wAWqj7JvAKx","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 19 — Failure Analysis\n     2→\n     3→## Overview\n     4→\n     5→1 failure out of 11 real-file test cases (90.9% pass rate). This is a **regression** — \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" passed in iteration 18 and now fails in iteration 19. The remaining 10 real files still pass.\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## Pattern 1: commonShort2 Expansion Admits Polish Body-Text as Candidates\n    10→\n    11→**Affected file:** `Smażona zielona fasolka.real.txt` (real file)\n    12→\n    13→**Affects:** Real files only. This specific regression cannot occur in generated files because the generated template files use English OCR content.\n    14→\n    15→---\n    16→\n    17→### What the file contains\n    18→\n    19→```\n    20→Line 0:  Smażona zielona fasolka          ← correct title (mixed-case Polish)\n    21→Line 1:  GREEN BEANS BORKEUM              ← ALL_CAPS English translation\n    22→Line 2:  그린빈 볶음                        ← Korean original\n    23→...\n    24→Line 21: No potelni rozprowadż oliwę z oliwek i smaż crosnek na duzym ogr\n    25→Line 23: Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno   ← \"Serve hot or cold\" (Polish)\n    26→Line 24: 64\n    27→```\n    28→\n    29→The correct answer is `Smażona zielona fasolka`. The file is a bilingual recipe page: Polish title on line 0, then an ALL_CAPS English/romanization translation on line 1.\n    30→\n    31→---\n    32→\n    33→### Why iteration 18 passed\n    34→\n    35→In iteration 18, `commonShort2` contained only basic Polish prepositions (`w`, `z`). The line `Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno` contained `\"na\"` — a 2-letter lowercase word not in commonShort2. The `isLikelyGarbled` multi-word check flagged `\"na\"` as a garbled fragment, causing the entire line to be filtered by `passesHardFilters`. Only `\"Smażona zielona fasolka\"` (and the now-suppressed bilingual translation pair) survived as candidates, so the single-title result was correct.\n    36→\n    37→---\n    38→\n    39→### What iteration 19 changed\n    40→\n    41→Iteration 19 added Polish prepositions to `commonShort2`:\n    42→\n    43→```typescript\n    44→\"ze\", \"bo\", \"na\", \"ni\", \"po\", \"ku\", \"od\", \"za\", \"co\",\n    45→```\n    46→\n    47→This was intended to fix titles like `Krem Grzybowy ze Śmietaną` (Pattern 2 from iter 18). It succeeded at that. However, it has a **collateral effect**: Polish body-text lines that previously failed the garbled-word check because they contained these prepositions now pass `passesHardFilters`.\n    48→\n    49→Specifically in this file:\n    50→\n    51→- **`\"Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno\"`** (line 23, \"Serve hot or cold\"):\n    52→  In iter 18: `\"na\"` triggered `hasGarbledWord` → filtered.\n    53→  In iter 19: `\"na\"` is in `commonShort2` → not flagged → **passes all hard filters**.\n    54→\n    55→- **`\"No potelni rozprowadż oliwę z oliwek i smaż crosnek na duzym ogr\"`** (line 21):\n    56→  Same mechanism — `\"na\"` passes in iter 19 but would have been caught in iter 18.\n    57→\n    58→Both lines now enter the candidate pool as single-line candidates.\n    59→\n    60→---\n    61→\n    62→### Why the algorithm fails\n    63→\n    64→The bilingual detection (unchanged between iter 18 and 19) correctly identifies `GREEN BEANS BORKEUM` as a translation of `Smażona zielona fasolka` and suppresses it from `scoredForThreshold`. This prevents the translation's ALL_CAPS bonuses from inflating the threshold. So far so good.\n    65→\n    66→However, the newly admitted body-text candidates are **not translations** — the bilingual detection has no mechanism to identify them. They enter the scoring pool as ordinary candidates.\n    67→\n    68→The failure path is most likely through the **multi-title guard**:\n    69→\n    70→1. After threshold filtering, `selected` contains `\"Smażona zielona fasolka\"` PLUS one or more body-text candidates (e.g., `\"Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno\"`).\n    71→2. `allCapsSelected = selected.filter(s => isAllCaps(s.text))` = **empty** (GREEN BEANS BORKEUM was suppressed; body-text lines are mixed-case).\n    72→3. When `allCapsSelected.length === 0`, the multi-title guard takes the implicit path: **keep all candidates**.\n    73→4. Both `\"Smażona zielona fasolka\"` and `\"Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno\"` survive dedup (neither is a substring of the other).\n    74→5. Result: `\"Smażona zielona fasolka + Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno\"` — does not match expected `\"Smażona zielona fasolka\"`.\n    75→\n    76→An alternative failure path (if embedding scores differ enough): the body-text candidate has a higher `thresholdScore` than `\"Smażona zielona fasolka\"`, inflating the threshold such that the title no longer passes `s.score >= threshold`. This would produce no result (or a fallback to the wrong candidate).\n    77→\n    78→---\n    79→\n    80→### Root cause summary\n    81→\n    82→The `commonShort2` expansion fixed real title failures (Pattern 2, iter 18) but also **weakened the garbled-word filter for Polish body text**. Polish recipe instructions frequently use short prepositions (`na`, `po`, `za`, `od`). Adding them to the \"not-garbled\" whitelist correctly admits Polish title words, but also admits Polish cooking instructions as candidates.\n    83→\n    84→The bilingual detection and other filters are not designed to handle this secondary effect. The consequence is a regression in a file that was previously correctly handled.\n    85→\n    86→---\n    87→\n    88→### Why this pattern affects only real files\n    89→\n    90→Generated test files use English OCR content built from templates. The body text is English (e.g., \"Beat egg whites until stiff peaks form\"), which is filtered by `looksLikeCookingInstruction` (added in iter 19 — covering this exact scenario). Polish cooking instructions like `\"Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno\"` do not start with English imperative verbs, so they bypass the cooking-instruction filter. Real files are more likely to contain Polish body text of this kind.\n    91→\n    92→---\n    93→\n    94→## No Other Patterns\n    95→\n    96→Only one real file fails. There are no generated-file failures in this iteration. The single failure is fully explained by the mechanism above.\n    97→\n    98→---\n    99→\n   100→## Suggested Fix Direction\n   101→\n   102→The problem is that `commonShort2` serves a dual purpose: it whitelists short words for the garbled-word check. Expanding it for Polish titles is correct, but it inadvertently whitelists the same short words that appear in Polish body text.\n   103→\n   104→Two non-exclusive approaches:\n   105→\n   106→1. **Extend `looksLikeCookingInstruction` to cover Polish imperative verbs** — add `Podawaj`, `Dodaj`, `Smaż`, `Gotuj`, `Odcedź`, etc. to the verb list. This would filter the specific body-text lines without touching the short-word logic.\n   107→\n   108→2. **Add a position-based tiebreak for zero-ALL_CAPS multi-candidate results** — when `allCapsSelected.length === 0` and multiple mixed-case candidates survive, prefer the one at position 0 (or the earliest) rather than keeping all. The title is almost always near the top of the document; late-appearing body-text candidates should lose to position-0 candidates.\n   109→\n   110→Option 2 is the safer general fix (it doesn't require enumerating Polish cooking verbs), but either would resolve this specific regression.\n   111→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01XdvAmX8uYeobcBc1WPNrCk","session_id":"8b8858bc-a11e-49e9-aee6-802d54bbaef0","uuid":"96a7a0a8-eca9-47a0-ab2c-d6882460208c"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01UX5csUq4wcRzppzT5BEKcR","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01VkeWR1i55PTdAtiPTEoyFM","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/20-3b20209/improvement-plan.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":79864,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":79864,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01XdvAmX8uYeobcBc1WPNrCk","session_id":"8b8858bc-a11e-49e9-aee6-802d54bbaef0","uuid":"c754b964-5632-412f-be77-343226779d68"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HyTurtbSabCmentvCyAXwJ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 20 — Failure Analysis\n     2→\n     3→## Overview\n     4→\n     5→1 failure out of 11 real-file test cases (90.9% pass rate). The failure is a **regression**:\n     6→`SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` passed in iteration 19 and now\n     7→fails in iteration 20. The remaining 10 real files still pass.\n     8→\n     9→---\n    10→\n    11→## Pattern 1: 8-Word Filter Blocks `/`-Separated Variant Titles\n    12→\n    13→**Affected file:** `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D).real.txt` (real file)\n    14→\n    15→**Affects:** Real files only (the 8-word filter is a new `passesHardFilters` guard added in\n    16→iteration 20; the generated test files that hit the 8-word range all use ` + ` or ` : `\n    17→separators, which are already whitelisted).\n    18→\n    19→---\n    20→\n    21→### What the file contains\n    22→\n    23→The OCR page contains two variations of saffron buns from the same cookbook spread. The first\n    24→~53 lines are the body of Variation 1 (whose heading appears near the middle: `FRON WHEAT BUNS\n    25→(VARIATION 1)` — a truncated OCR fragment of \"SAFFRON\"). The target recipe starts at lines 54–55:\n    26→\n    27→```\n    28→Line 54: SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\n    29→Line 55: / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\n    30→```\n    31→\n    32→The test harness filename uses `:` as a filesystem-safe substitute for `/`, so the expected\n    33→title (after `normalize_separators` converts `:` → `/`) is:\n    34→`SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`.\n    35→\n    36→---\n    37→\n    38→### Why iteration 19 passed\n    39→\n    40→In iteration 19, `passesHardFilters` had no word-count ceiling. The continuation pre-merge step\n    41→(which merges a line into its predecessor when it starts with `/`, `&`, `+`, `:`, or `(`)\n    42→correctly merged lines 54–55 into a single candidate:\n    43→\n    44→```\n    45→SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\n    46→```\n    47→\n    48→This candidate passed all hard filters, qualified as a structural heading (`isStructuralHeading`),\n    49→and scored well on embedding similarity. The algorithm returned it as the title.\n    50→\n    51→---\n    52→\n    53→### What iteration 20 changed\n    54→\n    55→Iteration 20 added this guard to `passesHardFilters` (line 282):\n    56→\n    57→```typescript\n    58→// Lines with ≥8 words are almost certainly body text, not titles.\n    59→// Exception: multi-title compounds with \" + \", \" : \", or \" & \" separators are allowed.\n    60→if (words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:&] /.test(text)) return false;\n    61→```\n    62→\n    63→The merged title `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` has 10 words\n    64→(SAFFRON, WHEAT, BUNS, WITH, QUARK, /, COTTAGE, CHEESE, (VARIATION, D)). It fails the guard\n    65→because `/` is **not** in the separator exception set (`+`, `:`, `&`).\n    66→\n    67→---\n    68→\n    69→### Why the algorithm fails\n    70→\n    71→1. The continuation pre-merge produces `\"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\"` as a single merged line.\n    72→2. `passesHardFilters` rejects it: 10 words ≥ 8, and the text contains ` / ` not ` + `, ` : `, or ` & `.\n    73→3. Because the pre-merge consumed line 55, `\"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\"` alone never appears in `mergedLines` — there is no standalone 5-word candidate for this title either.\n    74→4. With the correct title absent from the candidate pool, the next-best structural heading is `\"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\"` — a truncated OCR fragment from the previous variation on the same page.\n    75→5. The truncation-detection code (which penalises \"FRON\" when \"SAFFRON\" is present as a longer candidate) cannot fire, because the full \"SAFFRON…\" candidate was eliminated before scoring.\n    76→6. The algorithm returns a wrong answer derived from the previous recipe's corrupted heading.\n    77→\n    78→---\n    79→\n    80→### Root cause summary\n    81→\n    82→The 8-word filter was added to fix body-text leakage (long Polish cooking-instruction sentences\n    83→escaping into candidates after the `commonShort2` expansion). The fix is correct in principle,\n    84→but its separator-exception whitelist is incomplete. Cookbook titles often use ` / ` to separate\n    85→a base recipe from a named variation (e.g. \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE\n    86→(VARIATION D)\"). The separator regex `/ [+:&] /` does not include `/`, so these legitimate\n    87→long titles are incorrectly discarded.\n    88→\n    89→The fix is minimal: add `/` to the exception regex so that ` / ` is treated the same way as\n    90→` + `, ` : `, and ` & `:\n    91→\n    92→```typescript\n    93→if (words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:&/] /.test(text)) return false;\n    94→```\n    95→\n    96→---\n    97→\n    98→## No Other Patterns\n    99→\n   100→Only one real file fails. There are no generated-file failures in this iteration. The single\n   101→failure is fully explained by the incomplete separator whitelist in the 8-word guard.\n   102→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01XdvAmX8uYeobcBc1WPNrCk","session_id":"8b8858bc-a11e-49e9-aee6-802d54bbaef0","uuid":"f4eb5398-df59-425f-93be-f3cc7d127cd9"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01UX5csUq4wcRzppzT5BEKcR","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_016Aocq3YtaNtazLcKg7VP8k","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/19-55b161b/improvement-plan.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":79864,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":79864,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01XdvAmX8uYeobcBc1WPNrCk","session_id":"8b8858bc-a11e-49e9-aee6-802d54bbaef0","uuid":"b67aaaca-efbe-423f-8efa-72fac33890f7"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VkeWR1i55PTdAtiPTEoyFM","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 20 → 21 Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Summary\n     4→\n     5→One failure, one root cause, one fix. The 8-word filter's separator exception regex is missing `/`, causing a correctly merged continuation title to be rejected.\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## Failure: 8-Word Filter Blocks `/`-Separated Variant Titles\n    10→\n    11→### Root cause\n    12→\n    13→The guard at `title-extractor.ts:282`:\n    14→\n    15→```typescript\n    16→if (words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:&] /.test(text)) return false;\n    17→```\n    18→\n    19→rejects `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` (10 words) because ` / ` is not matched by the character class `[+:&]`. The continuation pre-merge step correctly merged lines 54–55 into this single candidate, but `passesHardFilters` discards it. Because the merge consumed line 55, the standalone 5-word prefix `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK` never enters the candidate pool either. The algorithm falls back to the wrong (truncated OCR) heading from the previous recipe on the page.\n    20→\n    21→### Fix\n    22→\n    23→Add `/` to the separator exception character class:\n    24→\n    25→**Before (line 282):**\n    26→```typescript\n    27→if (words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:&] /.test(text)) return false;\n    28→```\n    29→\n    30→**After:**\n    31→```typescript\n    32→if (words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:&/] /.test(text)) return false;\n    33→```\n    34→\n    35→This is consistent with the existing treatment of `/` elsewhere in the pipeline:\n    36→- The continuation pre-merge already recognizes `/` as a continuation character (`/^[/&+:(]/.test(nextText)` at line 407).\n    37→- The continuation-join protection logic already handles `/` (`/^[/&+:(]/.test(remainder)` at line 773).\n    38→- The multi-slash breadcrumb filter (line 272) already permits single-`/` titles through.\n    39→\n    40→Adding `/` to the 8-word exception makes the hard filter consistent with these existing rules.\n    41→\n    42→### Risk assessment\n    43→\n    44→**Low.** The `/` separator in cookbook titles is structurally identical to ` + `, ` : `, and ` & ` — it separates a base recipe name from a variation/subtitle. No body-text sentence uses ` / ` as a word separator, so this change cannot admit false positives. The existing 2-slash breadcrumb filter (line 272) still blocks navigation lines like `/ Jesien / Zupy`.\n    45→\n    46→### Expected impact\n    47→\n    48→- The SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS regression is fixed: the merged 10-word title passes `passesHardFilters`, qualifies as a structural heading, and wins scoring as it did in iteration 19.\n    49→- All other test cases remain unaffected (no other candidate is blocked by the 8-word filter with a single `/`).\n    50→- Real-file pass rate returns to 100% (11/11).\n    51→\n    52→---\n    53→\n    54→## No other changes needed\n    55→\n    56→No other patterns are failing. The pipeline's core architecture (continuation pre-merge → caps coalescence → candidate building → embedding scoring → structural heading selection → dedup) is working correctly for all 11 real files and all generated files. This iteration requires only the one-character regex fix described above.\n    57→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01XdvAmX8uYeobcBc1WPNrCk","session_id":"8b8858bc-a11e-49e9-aee6-802d54bbaef0","uuid":"a042327e-c7fc-41e7-ac89-76e2404ad514"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_016Aocq3YtaNtazLcKg7VP8k","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 19 → 20: Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Executive Summary\n     4→\n     5→1 failure out of 11 real-file test cases (90.9% pass rate). This is a **regression** — `Smażona zielona fasolka` passed in iteration 18 but fails in iteration 19. The root cause is that the `commonShort2` expansion (added to fix Pattern 2 from iter 18) collaterally admits Polish body-text lines as candidates. The multi-title guard then fails to reduce the result to a single title.\n     6→\n     7→This plan proposes 3 changes — two targeted fixes and one structural improvement — that together eliminate the regression while hardening against the broader class of \"body text leaking into candidates\" failures.\n     8→\n     9→---\n    10→\n    11→## Root Cause Analysis\n    12→\n    13→### Why the regression happened\n    14→\n    15→Iteration 19 added Polish prepositions (`na`, `po`, `za`, `od`, etc.) to `commonShort2` to fix titles like `Krem Grzybowy ze Śmietaną`. This was correct — those titles were being garble-filtered. But the same short words appear frequently in Polish cooking instructions:\n    16→\n    17→- `\"Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno\"` (line 24, \"Serve hot or cold\") — `na` now passes\n    18→- `\"No potelni rozprowadż oliwę z oliwek i smaż crosnek na duzym ogr\"` (line 22) — `na` now passes\n    19→\n    20→Both lines enter the candidate pool. The bilingual detection correctly suppresses `GREEN BEANS BORKEUM` (the ALL_CAPS translation). But these body-text lines aren't translations — they're cooking instructions in Polish. No existing filter catches them.\n    21→\n    22→### Why the multi-title guard doesn't help\n    23→\n    24→After threshold filtering, `selected` contains `Smażona zielona fasolka` plus one or more body-text candidates. The multi-title guard checks `allCapsSelected`:\n    25→\n    26→```\n    27→allCapsSelected = selected.filter(s => isAllCaps(s.text)) → empty\n    28→```\n    29→\n    30→When `allCapsSelected.length === 0`, the guard's implicit path is: **keep all candidates**. Both the title and the body-text line survive dedup (neither is a substring of the other). Result: `\"Smażona zielona fasolka + Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno\"`.\n    31→\n    32→### The fundamental gap\n    33→\n    34→The current pipeline has strong filters for:\n    35→- English cooking instructions (via `looksLikeCookingInstruction`)\n    36→- Garbled OCR text (via `isLikelyGarbled`)\n    37→- Ingredients, metadata, section labels\n    38→\n    39→But it has **no filter for Polish cooking instructions**. The English cooking-instruction filter (`COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`) only recognizes English imperative verbs. Polish imperative verbs (`Podawaj`, `Dodaj`, `Smaż`, `Gotuj`) are invisible to it.\n    40→\n    41→Additionally, the multi-title guard's zero-ALL_CAPS path is a **no-op** — it keeps everything. This is a latent bug: in a single-recipe page with no ALL_CAPS titles, any mixed-case body text that passes filters will be returned alongside the real title.\n    42→\n    43→---\n    44→\n    45→## Change 1: Extend `looksLikeCookingInstruction` to Polish Imperative Verbs\n    46→\n    47→### What\n    48→\n    49→Add a parallel regex for Polish cooking verbs to the `looksLikeCookingInstruction` function.\n    50→\n    51→### Why\n    52→\n    53→The English cooking-instruction filter was added in iter 19 (Change 5 from the iter 18 plan) and works well for English garbage prologues. The same principle applies to Polish cooking instructions: they start with imperative verbs and are multi-word sentences. No recipe title starts with `Podawaj` (serve), `Dodaj` (add), `Smaż` (fry), or `Gotuj` (cook) followed by 3+ more words.\n    54→\n    55→### Proposed Change\n    56→\n    57→**Before:**\n    58→```typescript\n    59→const COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS = /^(beat|fold|stir|mix|add|pour|bake|cook|cool|remove|place|combine|whisk|knead|roll|spread|brush|slice|chop|dice|mince|drain|rinse|peel|grate|melt|simmer|boil|fry|sauté|saute|roast|grill|broil|steam|let|set|transfer|serve|garnish|arrange|sprinkle|season|preheat|cover|uncover|reduce|bring|toss|cut|trim|shape|form)\\b/i;\n    60→\n    61→function looksLikeCookingInstruction(text: string): boolean {\n    62→  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n    63→  if (words.length < 4) return false;\n    64→  return COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS.test(text.trim());\n    65→}\n    66→```\n    67→\n    68→**After:**\n    69→```typescript\n    70→const COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS = /^(beat|fold|stir|mix|add|pour|bake|cook|cool|remove|place|combine|whisk|knead|roll|spread|brush|slice|chop|dice|mince|drain|rinse|peel|grate|melt|simmer|boil|fry|sauté|saute|roast|grill|broil|steam|let|set|transfer|serve|garnish|arrange|sprinkle|season|preheat|cover|uncover|reduce|bring|toss|cut|trim|shape|form)\\b/i;\n    71→\n    72→// Polish imperative cooking verbs (with OCR-resilient forms — no diacritics required).\n    73→// These cover the most common recipe instruction starters. Includes common OCR-corrupted\n    74→// forms (e.g., \"Smaż\" → \"Smaz\", \"Dodaj\" → \"Dodaj\").\n    75→// Note: only verbs that NEVER start a recipe title. \"Piecz\" (bake) is excluded because\n    76→// \"Pieczeń\" (roast) and \"Pieczarki\" (mushrooms) share the prefix.\n    77→const POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS = /^(podawaj|dodaj|dodawaj|sma[zż]|gotuj|odced[zź]|wymiesza[jJ]|miesza[jJ]|wlej|nalej|przygotuj|zagotuj|pokr[oó]j|obierz|wrzuc|wrzuć|usma[zż]|podsma[zż]|prze[lł][oó][zż]|zblenduj|ubij|roztrzepaj|rozprowad[zź]|wyrob|zamieszaj|posyp|polej|odstaw|na[lł][oó][zż]|przykryj|odkryj|wstaw|zdejmij|ods[aą]cz|rozgrzej|posiekaj|zetrzyj|wy[lł][oó][zż]|wyjmij|ukr[oó]j|przekr[oó]j|formuj|ugniataj|rozwałkuj)\\b/i;\n    78→\n    79→function looksLikeCookingInstruction(text: string): boolean {\n    80→  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n    81→  if (words.length < 4) return false;\n    82→  if (COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS.test(text.trim())) return true;\n    83→  if (POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS.test(text.trim())) return true;\n    84→  return false;\n    85→}\n    86→```\n    87→\n    88→### Directly affected lines in the failing file\n    89→\n    90→- `\"Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno\"` — starts with `Podawaj`, 6 words → **filtered**\n    91→- `\"No potelni rozprowadż oliwę z oliwek i smaż crosnek na duzym ogr\"` — starts with `No`, not a verb → **not filtered by this change** (handled by Change 2 instead)\n    92→\n    93→### Risk assessment\n    94→\n    95→**Low risk.** The same principle as the English filter: imperative cooking verbs followed by 4+ words are never recipe titles. Polish recipe titles use nouns, adjectives, or past participles (`Smażona` = \"fried\", adjective), not imperative forms (`Smaż` = \"fry!\", imperative).\n    96→\n    97→Edge cases verified:\n    98→- `Smażona zielona fasolka` — starts with `Smażona` (adjective), not `Smaż` (imperative) → **safe**\n    99→- `Gotowane pierogi` — starts with `Gotowane` (past participle), not `Gotuj` → **safe**\n   100→- `Dodatkowe sosy` — starts with `Dodatkowe` (adjective), not `Dodaj` → **safe**\n   101→\n   102→### Expected impact\n   103→\n   104→Directly filters `Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno` and similar Polish instruction lines. Prevents this class of false positives across all files with Polish body text.\n   105→\n   106→---\n   107→\n   108→## Change 2: Position-Based Tiebreak for Zero-ALL_CAPS Multi-Candidate Results\n   109→\n   110→### What\n   111→\n   112→When the multi-title guard encounters multiple surviving candidates and **none** are ALL_CAPS, prefer the earliest candidate (lowest position) rather than keeping all.\n   113→\n   114→### Why\n   115→\n   116→The zero-ALL_CAPS path in the multi-title guard currently keeps all candidates:\n   117→\n   118→```typescript\n   119→if (selected.length > 1) {\n   120→  const allCapsSelected = selected.filter((s) => isAllCaps(s.text));\n   121→  if (allCapsSelected.length >= 2) {\n   122→    // ... multi-recipe page logic\n   123→  } else if (allCapsSelected.length === 1) {\n   124→    // ... single ALL_CAPS logic\n   125→  }\n   126→  // allCapsSelected.length === 0 → implicit: keep all ← THE BUG\n   127→}\n   128→```\n   129→\n   130→This implicit \"keep all\" is wrong for single-recipe pages. On a single-recipe page with a mixed-case title, any body-text line that leaks through filters becomes a second \"title\". The title is almost always the earliest candidate (position 0 or near it). Body-text lines appear later in the document.\n   131→\n   132→A true multi-title page with zero ALL_CAPS candidates (two mixed-case recipe titles on one page) is extremely rare in this corpus. And even in that case, returning just the first title is an acceptable degradation.\n   133→\n   134→### Proposed Change\n   135→\n   136→**Before (implicit):**\n   137→```typescript\n   138→// When allCapsSelected.length === 0: no action, keep all selected\n   139→```\n   140→\n   141→**After:**\n   142→```typescript\n   143→} else {\n   144→  // Zero ALL_CAPS survivors → single mixed-case recipe page.\n   145→  // No structural signal for multi-recipe detection. Use positional tiebreak:\n   146→  // the title is almost always the earliest candidate.\n   147→  // Score-based tiebreak within a position tolerance: if two candidates are within\n   148→  // 3 positions of each other, prefer the higher-scoring one.\n   149→  selected.sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position);\n   150→  const earliest = selected[0];\n   151→  const closeCompetitors = selected.filter(\n   152→    (s) => s.position <= earliest.position + 3 && s.score > earliest.score\n   153→  );\n   154→  selected = closeCompetitors.length > 0\n   155→    ? [closeCompetitors.reduce((a, b) => a.score > b.score ? a : b)]\n   156→    : [earliest];\n   157→}\n   158→```\n   159→\n   160→### Why a position tolerance\n   161→\n   162→Sometimes the title is at position 1 or 2 (after a blank line or a garbled fragment that was filtered). A rigid \"always pick position 0\" would miss these cases. The tolerance of 3 positions allows the algorithm to pick a higher-scoring candidate that's very close to position 0, while still strongly preferring early candidates over body-text lines at positions 20+.\n   163→\n   164→### Trace through the failing file\n   165→\n   166→```\n   167→Candidates after threshold: [\n   168→  \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" (position 0, score ~0.25),\n   169→  \"Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno\" (position 23, score ~0.12),  ← if Change 1 doesn't catch it\n   170→  (possibly other body-text lines)\n   171→]\n   172→allCapsSelected = [] → zero ALL_CAPS path\n   173→earliest = \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" (position 0)\n   174→closeCompetitors within 3 positions with higher score = none\n   175→selected = [\"Smażona zielona fasolka\"] ✓\n   176→```\n   177→\n   178→Even if Change 1 misses a particular body-text line (e.g., one that doesn't start with a known verb), Change 2 catches it by position.\n   179→\n   180→### Risk assessment\n   181→\n   182→**Low risk.** The only scenario where this could regress is a genuine multi-recipe page with zero ALL_CAPS titles. In the current corpus:\n   183→- All multi-recipe pages use ALL_CAPS titles (handled by the `allCapsSelected.length >= 2` branch)\n   184→- No test file has two mixed-case recipe titles on one page\n   185→- If such a file appears in the future, the fix is to handle it in the `allCapsSelected >= 2` branch (which already has multi-recipe logic), not in the zero-ALL_CAPS path\n   186→\n   187→### Expected impact\n   188→\n   189→Eliminates the regression in `Smażona zielona fasolka`. Also prevents any future regression where body-text lines leak into the zero-ALL_CAPS path.\n   190→\n   191→---\n   192→\n   193→## Change 3: Long-Line Body-Text Filter Based on Word Count\n   194→\n   195→### What\n   196→\n   197→Add a filter in `passesHardFilters` that rejects candidates with high word counts (≥8 words) that don't look like multi-part titles.\n   198→\n   199→### Why\n   200→\n   201→Recipe titles rarely exceed 7 words. Lines with 8+ words are almost always cooking instructions, ingredient descriptions, or body text. The line `\"No potelni rozprowadż oliwę z oliwek i smaż crosnek na duzym ogr\"` has 12 words — no recipe title is that long.\n   202→\n   203→Currently there's a max *character* length (80 chars) but no max *word* count. A 12-word line at 65 characters passes the character limit.\n   204→\n   205→### Proposed Change\n   206→\n   207→Add to `passesHardFilters`, after the existing length check:\n   208→\n   209→```typescript\n   210→// Lines with ≥8 words are almost certainly body text, not titles.\n   211→// Exception: multi-title compounds with \" + \" or \" : \" separators are allowed\n   212→// (they're structurally distinct from continuous prose).\n   213→const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n   214→if (words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:] /.test(text)) return false;\n   215→```\n   216→\n   217→### Directly affected lines in the failing file\n   218→\n   219→- `\"No potelni rozprowadż oliwę z oliwek i smaż crosnek na duzym ogr\"` — 12 words → **filtered**\n   220→- `\"Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno\"` — 6 words → **not filtered** (caught by Change 1 instead)\n   221→- `\"Smażona zielona fasolka\"` — 3 words → **safe**\n   222→\n   223→### Risk assessment\n   224→\n   225→**Very low risk.** Checked against all passing test expectations:\n   226→- Longest passing title: `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` — 9 \"words\" but contains ` : ` separator → exception applies\n   227→- `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander` — 8 words, but actually 7 without the comma-separated part... let me check. The words split: `[\"Baked\", \"Eggs\", \"with\", \"Feta,\", \"Harissa\", \"Tomato\", \"Sauce\", \"&\", \"Coriander\"]` = 9 words. However, this contains no ` + ` or ` : ` separator. **This would be falsely filtered.**\n   228→\n   229→**Revised threshold:** Use 10 words instead of 8 to accommodate long legitimate titles:\n   230→\n   231→```typescript\n   232→if (words.length >= 10 && !/ [+:&] /.test(text)) return false;\n   233→```\n   234→\n   235→Re-check:\n   236→- `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"` — 9 words, contains ` & ` → exception applies → **safe**\n   237→- `\"HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION\"` — 6 words → **safe**\n   238→- `\"No potelni rozprowadż oliwę z oliwek i smaż crosnek na duzym ogr\"` — 12 words, no separator → **filtered**\n   239→\n   240→Alternatively, if we want a tighter bound, use 8 words with the `&` exception:\n   241→\n   242→```typescript\n   243→if (words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:&] /.test(text)) return false;\n   244→```\n   245→\n   246→- `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"` — contains ` & ` → **safe**\n   247→- `\"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\"` — contains ` + ` → **safe**\n   248→\n   249→This is the safer option. Use 8 words with the `+`, `:`, and `&` separator exception.\n   250→\n   251→### Expected impact\n   252→\n   253→Filters long body-text lines (12+ words) that slip through other checks. Acts as a safety net for the class of failures where body text lines are too long to be titles but don't start with known cooking verbs.\n   254→\n   255→---\n   256→\n   257→## Interaction Between Changes\n   258→\n   259→The three changes form defense-in-depth layers:\n   260→\n   261→1. **Change 1 (Polish cooking verbs):** Catches the specific `Podawaj...` line that caused this regression. Language-specific, precise.\n   262→\n   263→2. **Change 2 (position tiebreak):** Catches ANY body-text line that leaks through filters, regardless of language. Structural, general-purpose.\n   264→\n   265→3. **Change 3 (word count filter):** Catches very long lines (12-word cooking instructions) that don't start with known verbs. Language-agnostic, simple.\n   266→\n   267→For the specific failing file:\n   268→- Line 22 (`No potelni...`, 12 words): caught by Change 3\n   269→- Line 24 (`Podawaj no gorqco...`, 6 words): caught by Change 1\n   270→- If either line somehow survives both filters: caught by Change 2 (position tiebreak)\n   271→\n   272→Even if only ONE of the three changes is applied, the regression is fixed. All three together provide resilience against future variants.\n   273→\n   274→---\n   275→\n   276→## Implementation Order\n   277→\n   278→1. **Change 2 (position tiebreak)** — most general, fixes the regression regardless of what else is done. Zero risk of breaking other tests. Implement first.\n   279→2. **Change 1 (Polish cooking verbs)** — precise, addresses the root cause at the filter level. Improves candidate quality for all Polish-text files.\n   280→3. **Change 3 (word count filter)** — safety net. Apply last, verify against full corpus.\n   281→\n   282→---\n   283→\n   284→## Expected Impact\n   285→\n   286→| Change | Files Fixed | Risk | Complexity |\n   287→|--------|-------------|------|------------|\n   288→| 1. Polish cooking verbs | 1 (Smażona zielona fasolka) + future Polish files | Low | Low |\n   289→| 2. Position tiebreak | 1 (same) + general hardening | Very low | Low |\n   290→| 3. Word count filter | 1 (same) + general hardening | Very low | Trivial |\n   291→\n   292→**Expected pass rate after changes: 11/11 (100%) on real files.**\n   293→\n   294→All three changes are mutually reinforcing. Any single change fixes the current regression. Together, they close the broader gap that made the regression possible.\n   295→\n   296→---\n   297→\n   298→## Not Addressed (Accepted)\n   299→\n   300→### The `commonShort2` dual-purpose tension\n   301→\n   302→The feedback correctly identifies that `commonShort2` serves a dual purpose: whitelisting short words for title candidates AND inadvertently whitelisting them in body text. We do NOT propose reverting the `commonShort2` expansion — it's still needed for titles like `Krem Grzybowy ze Śmietaną`. Instead, we address the collateral effect through better downstream filtering (Changes 1–3).\n   303→\n   304→### OCR character substitution and missing words\n   305→\n   306→These remain accepted limitations (as noted in iter 18 plan). They require OCR-level fixes, not title-extraction logic.\n   307→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01XdvAmX8uYeobcBc1WPNrCk","session_id":"8b8858bc-a11e-49e9-aee6-802d54bbaef0","uuid":"3b69f2a4-13b3-45d8-bc34-cb345842de4d"}
