{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01XdvAmX8uYeobcBc1WPNrCk","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect. Now I have all the context. Let me provide a comprehensive summary:\n\n## Summary of Title Extraction Loop Evolution\n\n### **Iteration 18** — Baseline with 54 failures (72.9% pass rate, real: 100%)\n\n**Key Issues Identified:**\n\n1. **Pattern 1 (largest, ~20 failures): ALL_CAPS vs. Title Case mismatch**\n   - Algorithm returns OCR text verbatim (`BARSZCZ`, `BEEF STEW`) but tests expect Title Case (`Barszcz`, `Beef Stew`)\n   - Root cause: No case normalization step in the pipeline\n\n2. **Pattern 2: Polish preposition `ze` triggers garbled-word false positive**\n   - `commonShort2` whitelist didn't include `\"ze\"` (Polish form of preposition)\n   - Titles like `Krem Grzybowy ze Śmietaną` were filtered out as garbled\n\n3. **Pattern 3: Two-word titles split across lines — dedup removes the compound**\n   - Single words (`Lamb`, `Stew`) survive, but the 2-line join (`Lamb Stew`) gets removed because each component is a substring of the whole\n   - Problem: dedup rule \"keep the shorter substring\" destroys the valid multi-word title\n\n4. **Pattern 4: Section labels block multi-line joins**\n   - `Zupy` (meaning \"soups\") is in `SECTION_LABELS`, so `Zupy Zimowe Warzywne` never gets generated as a compound candidate\n\n5. **Pattern 5: Long OCR garbage prologues bypass burst detection**\n   - Template files start with 28-35 lines of long garbage (30-55 chars each)\n   - `findBurstEnd` only skips SHORT + GARBLED lines (< 20 chars), so long garbage lines are processed\n   - These garbage lines pass hard filters and become competing candidates\n\n6. **Pattern 6: Season header (`SEZON: WIOSNA`) wins over the actual title**\n   - ALL_CAPS header gets structural + position bonuses, outscoring the actual mixed-case title\n\n7. **Pattern 7: Parenthetical English subtitles merged into title**\n   - Continuation pre-merge merges lines starting with `(` into preceding line\n   - Example: `PIEROGI RUSKIE (Boiled Dumplings with Potato and Cheese)` should be just `PIEROGI RUSKIE`\n\n8. **Pattern 8: Compound titles destroyed by substring dedup**\n   - Example: `HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION` is removed because it contains the later section header `DILL SAUCE VARIATION` as a substring\n\n**Minor patterns:** Page number prefix blocks title, OCR character substitution, missing words from OCR split.\n\n---\n\n### **Iteration 19** — Added Polish prepositions to `commonShort2` (90.9% pass rate, real: 100%)\n\n**Changes Made:**\n- Extended `commonShort2` with Polish prepositions: `\"ze\", \"bo\", \"na\", \"ni\", \"po\", \"ku\", \"od\", \"za\", \"co\"`\n- Added `looksLikeCookingInstruction` English cooking verb filter to block garbage prologues\n- Fixes Pattern 2 (Polish preposition filtering)\n\n**New Regression Discovered:**\n- File: `Smażona zielona fasolka.real.txt` (1 real file failure)\n- Root cause: Adding `\"na\"` to `commonShort2` **collaterally** admits Polish body-text lines as candidates:\n  - `\"Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno\"` (line 24, \"Serve hot or cold\")\n  - `\"No potelni rozprowadż oliwę z oliwek i smaż crosnek na duzym ogr\"` (line 22)\n  - Both contain `\"na\"` which is now whitelisted\n- These lines are NOT filtered by the English cooking-instruction check (they start with Polish words, not English verbs)\n- Multi-title guard's \"zero ALL_CAPS\" path just keeps all candidates, resulting in: `\"Smażona zielona fasolka + Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno\"`\n\n**Key insight:** The `commonShort2` expansion serves dual purpose — it whitelists short words for *title* candidates AND for *body-text* candidates. The collateral effect is unavoidable at the short-word level; must be addressed downstream.\n\n---\n\n### **Iteration 20** — Added 8-word filter (90.9% pass rate, real: 100%)\n\n**Changes Made:**\n1. Added hard filter: reject lines with ≥8 words unless they contain ` + `, ` : `, or ` & ` separators\n2. Designed to block long Polish cooking instruction sentences that pass the short-word check\n\n**New Regression Discovered:**\n- File: `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D).real.txt` (1 real file failure, different from iter 19)\n- Root cause: The 8-word filter exception only whitelists ` + `, ` : `, and ` & ` separators\n- The continuation pre-merge correctly merges lines 54–55 into: `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` (10 words)\n- But the hard filter rejects it because ` / ` is **not** in the separator whitelist\n- The standalone 5-word prefix never appears (it was consumed by the merge)\n- Algorithm falls back to wrong answer from previous recipe\n\n**Key insight:** The 8-word filter's separator exception is incomplete. Cookbook titles use ` / ` just like ` + `, ` : `, and ` & ` to separate base recipe from variations.\n\n---\n\n## **Improvement Plans**\n\n### **Iteration 19 → 20 Plan (NOT yet implemented)**\n\nProposed 3-layer defense-in-depth:\n\n1. **Change 1:** Extend `looksLikeCookingInstruction` with Polish imperative verbs\n   - Add regex for: `podawaj`, `dodaj`, `smaż`, `gotuj`, `odcedź`, etc.\n   - Catches: `\"Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno\"` (line 24)\n\n2. **Change 2:** Position-based tiebreak for zero-ALL_CAPS multi-candidate results\n   - When no ALL_CAPS candidates survive and multiple mixed-case candidates remain, prefer the earliest one (position 0 or within 3 positions if higher score)\n   - Root cause fix: the zero-ALL_CAPS path is currently a no-op (\"keep all\"), which is wrong for single-recipe pages\n   - Catches: any body-text line that leaks through, regardless of language\n\n3. **Change 3:** Word-count hard filter with separator exceptions\n   - Reject lines with ≥8 words unless they contain ` + `, ` : `, or ` & ` separators\n   - Catches: `\"No potelni rozprowadż oliwę z oliwek i smaż crosnek na duzym ogr\"` (line 22, 12 words)\n\n**Status:** Plan written but **NOT applied yet**. This plan was designed to fix both the iter 19 regression (`Smażona zielona fasolka`) AND to prevent future leakage. However, iter 20 introduced a NEW regression (`SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS`) while still having the iter 19 one.\n\n---\n\n### **Iteration 20 → 21 Plan (simple, specific)**\n\nSingle targeted fix for the iter 20 regression:\n\n- **Problem:** The 8-word filter's separator exception regex is `/ [+:&] /` (missing `/`)\n- **Fix:** Change to `/ [+:&/] /` to include `/` separators\n\nThis is a minimal, low-risk one-character fix that makes the hard filter consistent with existing rules (continuation pre-merge, continuation-join protection, breadcrumb filter all already recognize `/`).\n\n**Expected impact:**\n- Fixes the SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS regression\n- All other test cases remain unaffected\n- Real-file pass rate returns to 100% (11/11)\n\n**Status:** Plan written, **NOT yet implemented**.\n\n---\n\n## **Current State (Iteration 21 has begun)**\n\nFrom `iter.txt`:\n- Iteration 20 shows 90.9% pass rate (one real file failure: SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS)\n- Iteration 21 shows 64.0% combined, 100.0% real (but contains generated-file regression data)\n\nThe feature branch `feat/title_extraction_loop` has uncommitted changes:\n- Modified: `.entire/settings.json`, `tools/title-loop/docs/iter.txt`, `tools/title-loop/title-loop.py`\n- Untracked: Generated test files and OCR generation scripts\n\n---\n\n## **Key Patterns Across Iterations**\n\n1. **Tension between whitelisting title words and filtering body text**\n   - `commonShort2` expansion needed for titles (`ze` in Polish), collaterally admits body text\n   - Solution: downstream filtering (cooking verbs, position tiebreak, word count)\n\n2. **Separator exceptions need to be complete**\n   - Recipe titles use multiple variants: ` + `, ` : `, ` & `, ` / ` for variations and sub-recipes\n   - Any filter with a separator exception must include ALL these\n\n3. **Multi-title guard has a latent bug**\n   - Zero-ALL_CAPS path is a no-op (\"keep all\")\n   - Wrong for single-recipe pages with mixed-case titles\n\n4. **Position is a strong signal**\n   - Recipe titles appear at or near position 0\n   - Body text and competing candidates appear later\n   - Position tiebreak is simple, effective, and low-risk\n\n---\n\nThis comprehensive iteration history shows a methodical, evidence-based debugging approach with clear root causes identified for each regression, and concrete improvement plans (though not yet fully implemented in the main code)."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a1bbc63ab138251a6 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 99830\ntool_uses: 7\nduration_ms: 39486</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8b8858bc-a11e-49e9-aee6-802d54bbaef0","uuid":"97e07213-8049-4bb4-86af-94b74ade7550","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Read these files and summarize the key changes and patterns from each iteration:\n- /Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/18-1d256ae/feedback.md\n- /Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/19-55b161b/feedback.md\n- /Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/20-3b20209/feedback.md\n\nAlso read the improvement plans if they exist:\n- /Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/20-3b20209/improvement-plan.md\n- /Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/19-55b161b/improvement-plan.md\n\nBe thorough - I need to understand the full history of what approaches have been tried.","agentId":"a1bbc63ab138251a6","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect. Now I have all the context. Let me provide a comprehensive summary:\n\n## Summary of Title Extraction Loop Evolution\n\n### **Iteration 18** — Baseline with 54 failures (72.9% pass rate, real: 100%)\n\n**Key Issues Identified:**\n\n1. **Pattern 1 (largest, ~20 failures): ALL_CAPS vs. Title Case mismatch**\n   - Algorithm returns OCR text verbatim (`BARSZCZ`, `BEEF STEW`) but tests expect Title Case (`Barszcz`, `Beef Stew`)\n   - Root cause: No case normalization step in the pipeline\n\n2. **Pattern 2: Polish preposition `ze` triggers garbled-word false positive**\n   - `commonShort2` whitelist didn't include `\"ze\"` (Polish form of preposition)\n   - Titles like `Krem Grzybowy ze Śmietaną` were filtered out as garbled\n\n3. **Pattern 3: Two-word titles split across lines — dedup removes the compound**\n   - Single words (`Lamb`, `Stew`) survive, but the 2-line join (`Lamb Stew`) gets removed because each component is a substring of the whole\n   - Problem: dedup rule \"keep the shorter substring\" destroys the valid multi-word title\n\n4. **Pattern 4: Section labels block multi-line joins**\n   - `Zupy` (meaning \"soups\") is in `SECTION_LABELS`, so `Zupy Zimowe Warzywne` never gets generated as a compound candidate\n\n5. **Pattern 5: Long OCR garbage prologues bypass burst detection**\n   - Template files start with 28-35 lines of long garbage (30-55 chars each)\n   - `findBurstEnd` only skips SHORT + GARBLED lines (< 20 chars), so long garbage lines are processed\n   - These garbage lines pass hard filters and become competing candidates\n\n6. **Pattern 6: Season header (`SEZON: WIOSNA`) wins over the actual title**\n   - ALL_CAPS header gets structural + position bonuses, outscoring the actual mixed-case title\n\n7. **Pattern 7: Parenthetical English subtitles merged into title**\n   - Continuation pre-merge merges lines starting with `(` into preceding line\n   - Example: `PIEROGI RUSKIE (Boiled Dumplings with Potato and Cheese)` should be just `PIEROGI RUSKIE`\n\n8. **Pattern 8: Compound titles destroyed by substring dedup**\n   - Example: `HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION` is removed because it contains the later section header `DILL SAUCE VARIATION` as a substring\n\n**Minor patterns:** Page number prefix blocks title, OCR character substitution, missing words from OCR split.\n\n---\n\n### **Iteration 19** — Added Polish prepositions to `commonShort2` (90.9% pass rate, real: 100%)\n\n**Changes Made:**\n- Extended `commonShort2` with Polish prepositions: `\"ze\", \"bo\", \"na\", \"ni\", \"po\", \"ku\", \"od\", \"za\", \"co\"`\n- Added `looksLikeCookingInstruction` English cooking verb filter to block garbage prologues\n- Fixes Pattern 2 (Polish preposition filtering)\n\n**New Regression Discovered:**\n- File: `Smażona zielona fasolka.real.txt` (1 real file failure)\n- Root cause: Adding `\"na\"` to `commonShort2` **collaterally** admits Polish body-text lines as candidates:\n  - `\"Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno\"` (line 24, \"Serve hot or cold\")\n  - `\"No potelni rozprowadż oliwę z oliwek i smaż crosnek na duzym ogr\"` (line 22)\n  - Both contain `\"na\"` which is now whitelisted\n- These lines are NOT filtered by the English cooking-instruction check (they start with Polish words, not English verbs)\n- Multi-title guard's \"zero ALL_CAPS\" path just keeps all candidates, resulting in: `\"Smażona zielona fasolka + Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno\"`\n\n**Key insight:** The `commonShort2` expansion serves dual purpose — it whitelists short words for *title* candidates AND for *body-text* candidates. The collateral effect is unavoidable at the short-word level; must be addressed downstream.\n\n---\n\n### **Iteration 20** — Added 8-word filter (90.9% pass rate, real: 100%)\n\n**Changes Made:**\n1. Added hard filter: reject lines with ≥8 words unless they contain ` + `, ` : `, or ` & ` separators\n2. Designed to block long Polish cooking instruction sentences that pass the short-word check\n\n**New Regression Discovered:**\n- File: `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D).real.txt` (1 real file failure, different from iter 19)\n- Root cause: The 8-word filter exception only whitelists ` + `, ` : `, and ` & ` separators\n- The continuation pre-merge correctly merges lines 54–55 into: `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEES