docs/12-0b9bd80/improvement-plan.md:132:  // Strip trailing colon/period, normalize whitespace, lowercase\ntools/title-loop/docs/12-0b9bd80/improvement-plan.md:133:  const normalized = text.trim().replace(/[:.]$/, \"\").toLowerCase();\ntools/title-loop/docs/12-0b9bd80/improvement-plan.md:134:  return SECTION_LABELS.has(normalized);\n/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/12-0b9bd80/improvement-plan.md-135-}\n/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/12-0b9bd80/improvement-plan.md-136-```\n/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/12-0b9bd80/improvement-plan.md-137-\n--\n/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/12-0b9bd80/improvement-plan.md-174-\ntools/title-loop/docs/12-0b9bd80/improvement-plan.md-175-**False positive risk:** Could a recipe be named \"Ingredients\" or \"Przygotowanie\"? In theory yes, but in practice no — these are generic section labels. The set is conservative (common unambiguous labels only). Multi-word labels like \"for the sauce\" are included because they appear in cookbook sub-section headers and would never be a standalone recipe title.\n/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/12-0b9bd80/improvement-plan.md-176-\ntools/title-loop/docs/12-0b9bd80/improvement-plan.md:177:**Note on trailing punctuation stripping:** Some OCR outputs produce `INGREDIENTS:` or `PRZYGOTOWANIE:` with a colon. The `replace(/[:.]$/, \"\")` ensures these match.\n/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/12-0b9bd80/improvement-plan.md-178-\n/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/12-0b9bd80/improvement-plan.md-179----\n/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/12-0b9bd80/improvement-plan.md-180-\n--\n/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/14-dfda596/feedback.md-24-  → removes \"LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA\" (contains \"with nigella\", shorter)\n/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/14-dfda596/feedback.md-25-```\n/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/14-dfda596/feedback.md-26-\ntools/title-loop/docs/14-dfda596/feedback.md:27:The structural heading prefix-removal guard (`fshLower.startsWith(sLower + \" \")`) does not help here because `WITH NIGELLA` is a **suffix** of `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA`, not a prefix — so it is not stripped before dedup runs.\n/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/14-dfda596/feedback.md-28-\ntools/title-loop/docs/14-dfda596/feedback.md-29-After dedup, `WITH NIGELLA` and `SEEDS` remain. Both are all-caps. The multi-title guard checks whether the second candidate (`SEEDS`, position 3) is followed by ingredient-like lines — it is not (body text follows) — so `isSubHeader = false` and both survive. Result: `WITH NIGELLA + SEEDS`.\n/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/14-dfda596/feedback.md-30-\n--\ntools/title-loop/docs/14-dfda596/feedback.md-47-Line 2: 그린빈 볶음                 (Korean script — filtered by garbled check)\n/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/14-dfda596/feedback.md-48-```\n/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/14-dfda596/feedback.md-49-\ntools/title-loop/docs/14-dfda596/feedback.md:50:`Smażona zielona fasolka` is mixed-case (Polish capitalizes only the first word of a title). It never qualifies as a structural heading (`isAllCaps` strips non-ASCII letters, checks only `[a-zA-Z]`, and `Smażona` contains lowercase ASCII letters).\n/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/14-dfda596/feedback.md-51-\n/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/14-dfda596/feedback.md-52-`GREEN BEANS BORKEUM` is all-caps with 3 words each ≥4 letters → it is a structural heading and receives the +0.10 structural bonus, pushing it above the mixed-case Polish title.\n/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/14-dfda596/feedback.md-53-\n--\ntools/title-loop/docs/4-4ecc5