{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Hbs6Tn6PrSRpdfBQ2gYeVe","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→Oscypek Smażony\n     2→Pan-Fried Smoked Cheese / Oscypek Grillé\n     3→\n     4→SKŁADNIKI (INGREDIENTS):\n     5→- 4 oscypek (traditional smoked cheese wheels, ~100g each)\n     6→- 2 tbsp vegetable oil\n     7→- 2 tbsp butter\n     8→- 4 tbsp lingonberry or cranberry preserve\n     9→- Fresh thyme sprigs for garnish\n    10→- Sea salt flakes\n    11→- Cracked black pepper\n    12→\n    13→PRZYGOTOWANIE (PREPARATION):\n    14→\n    15→Remove oscypek from refrigerator 15 minutes before cooking to bring to room temperature.\n    16→This prevents cheese from hardening when fried.\n    17→\n    18→Heat oil and butter together in large skillet over medium-high heat until butter foam\n    19→subsides. Temperature should be just below smoking point.\n    20→\n    21→Carefully place oscypek wheels in pan, being gentle not to break delicate shape. Fry\n    22→2-3 minutes per side until golden crust forms. Cheese should remain firm inside while\n    23→exterior caramelizes slightly.\n    24→\n    25→Transfer to serving plates immediately. Top with generous spoonful of lingonberry preserve\n    26→and fresh thyme sprigs. Season with sea salt and cracked pepper.\n    27→\n    28→SERVING SUGGESTIONS:\n    29→Serve immediately while still warm. Pairs well with crusty bread, fresh vegetables, or\n    30→green salad. In Poland, often accompanied by horseradish sauce or mustard.\n    31→\n    32→TIPS:\n    33→If oscypek unavailable, can substitute halloumi cheese or fresh mozzarella, though flavor\n    34→and texture will differ from traditional mountain cheese. Keep temperature consistent to\n    35→achieve perfect golden exterior and creamy interior.\n    36→\n    37→Serves 2-4 as appetizer or light main course.\n    38→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8b8858bc-a11e-49e9-aee6-802d54bbaef0","uuid":"6943be3a-bbf3-48f4-b4a1-f9fc2a2b8fc4","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/input/Oscypek Smażony.generated.21.txt","content":"Oscypek Smażony\nPan-Fried Smoked Cheese / Oscypek Grillé\n\nSKŁADNIKI (INGREDIENTS):\n- 4 oscypek (traditional smoked cheese wheels, ~100g each)\n- 2 tbsp vegetable oil\n- 2 tbsp butter\n- 4 tbsp lingonberry or cranberry preserve\n- Fresh thyme sprigs for garnish\n- Sea salt flakes\n- Cracked black pepper\n\nPRZYGOTOWANIE (PREPARATION):\n\nRemove oscypek from refrigerator 15 minutes before cooking to bring to room temperature.\nThis prevents cheese from hardening when fried.\n\nHeat oil and butter together in large skillet over medium-high heat until butter foam\nsubsides. Temperature should be just below smoking point.\n\nCarefully place oscypek wheels in pan, being gentle not to break delicate shape. Fry\n2-3 minutes per side until golden crust forms. Cheese should remain firm inside while\nexterior caramelizes slightly.\n\nTransfer to serving plates immediately. Top with generous spoonful of lingonberry preserve\nand fresh thyme sprigs. Season with sea salt and cracked pepper.\n\nSERVING SUGGESTIONS:\nServe immediately while still warm. Pairs well with crusty bread, fresh vegetables, or\ngreen salad. In Poland, often accompanied by horseradish sauce or mustard.\n\nTIPS:\nIf oscypek unavailable, can substitute halloumi cheese or fresh mozzarella, though flavor\nand texture will differ from traditional mountain cheese. Keep temperature consistent to\nachieve perfect golden exterior and creamy interior.\n\nServes 2-4 as appetizer or light main course.\n","numLines":38,"startLine":1,"totalLines":38}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Bm85EPEUZwNKAVPrTzDDti","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→FISH AND SEAFOOD | Page 156\n     2→\n     3→Śledzie w Śmietanie\n     4→\n     5→156 | Makes about 20 pieces | Preparation time: 30 minutes plus overnight soaking\n     6→\n     7→INGREDIENTS:\n     8→8-10 salted herring fillets\n     9→1 large onion, sliced thin\n    10→3 bay leaves\n    11→½ teaspoon black peppercorns\n    12→1 cup sour cream\n    13→3 tablespoons fresh lemon juice\n    14→2 tablespoons sugar\n    15→1 tablespoon whole grain mustard\n    16→¼ teaspoon salt\n    17→¼ teaspoon pepper\n    18→2 tablespoons fresh dill, chopped\n    19→\n    20→INSTRUCTIONS:\n    21→1. Soak herring fillets in cold water overnight to remove excess salt\n    22→2. Cut soaked fillets into bite-sized pieces\n    23→3. Layer herring pieces in glass jar with sliced onion\n    24→4. Add bay leaves and peppercorns between layers\n    25→5. In separate bowl, whisk together sour cream, lemon juice, sugar, mustard\n    26→6. Season with salt and pepper\n    27→7. Pour sour cream mixture over herring and onions\n    28→8. Cover jar and refrigerate at least 24 hours before serving\n    29→9. Garnish with fresh dill before serving\n    30→\n    31→SERVING:\n    32→Serve as an appetizer or side dish with rye bread and butter.\n    33→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8b8858bc-a11e-49e9-aee6-802d54bbaef0","uuid":"8e1bf428-3d9a-472e-8fb9-01fd6a876528","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/input/Śledzie w Śmietanie.generated.21.txt","content":"FISH AND SEAFOOD | Page 156\n\nŚledzie w Śmietanie\n\n156 | Makes about 20 pieces | Preparation time: 30 minutes plus overnight soaking\n\nINGREDIENTS:\n8-10 salted herring fillets\n1 large onion, sliced thin\n3 bay leaves\n½ teaspoon black peppercorns\n1 cup sour cream\n3 tablespoons fresh lemon juice\n2 tablespoons sugar\n1 tablespoon whole grain mustard\n¼ teaspoon salt\n¼ teaspoon pepper\n2 tablespoons fresh dill, chopped\n\nINSTRUCTIONS:\n1. Soak herring fillets in cold water overnight to remove excess salt\n2. Cut soaked fillets into bite-sized pieces\n3. Layer herring pieces in glass jar with sliced onion\n4. Add bay leaves and peppercorns between layers\n5. In separate bowl, whisk together sour cream, lemon juice, sugar, mustard\n6. Season with salt and pepper\n7. Pour sour cream mixture over herring and onions\n8. Cover jar and refrigerate at least 24 hours before serving\n9. Garnish with fresh dill before serving\n\nSERVING:\nServe as an appetizer or side dish with rye bread and butter.\n","numLines":33,"startLine":1,"totalLines":33}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01JgBJ7jRvNfVMV4UMHLAHha","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→Spring | Pasta Main Courses | PREP TIME: 30 MIN | COOKING TIME: 15 MIN\n     2→\n     3→SPINACH AND RICOTTA RAVIOLI\n     4→\n     5→For the pasta dough:\n     6→- 400 g all-purpose flour\n     7→- 4 eggs\n     8→- 1 tablespoon salt\n     9→- 2 tablespoons olive oil\n    10→\n    11→For the filling:\n    12→- 250 g fresh spinach, cleaned\n    13→- 250 g ricotta cheese\n    14→- 50 g Parmesan cheese, grated\n    15→- 1 egg\n    16→- Nutmeg, salt and pepper to taste\n    17→- 2 tablespoons pine nuts (optional)\n    18→\n    19→For the sauce:\n    20→- 3 tablespoons butter\n    21→- 12 sage leaves\n    22→- Salt and pepper to taste\n    23→\n    24→Instructions:\n    25→1. Make pasta dough: combine flour, eggs, salt and olive oil. Knead until smooth and elastic.\n    26→2. Wrap in plastic wrap and rest for 30 minutes.\n    27→3. Cook spinach until wilted, squeeze dry, chop finely.\n    28→4. Mix ricotta, spinach, Parmesan, egg, nutmeg, salt and pepper.\n    29→5. Roll pasta thin on floured surface.\n    30→6. Cut circles with cutter, fill center, fold and seal edges.\n    31→7. Bring pot of salted water to boil.\n    32→8. Cook ravioli until they float, then 2 minutes more.\n    33→9. Melt butter in pan with sage leaves.\n    34→10. Toss ravioli with butter, sage, salt and pepper.\n    35→11. Serve immediately with extra Parmesan.\n    36→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8b8858bc-a11e-49e9-aee6-802d54bbaef0","uuid":"89313229-8b15-4054-8828-583f6bcd2713","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/input/Spinach and Ricotta Ravioli.generated.21.txt","content":"Spring | Pasta Main Courses | PREP TIME: 30 MIN | COOKING TIME: 15 MIN\n\nSPINACH AND RICOTTA RAVIOLI\n\nFor the pasta dough:\n- 400 g all-purpose flour\n- 4 eggs\n- 1 tablespoon salt\n- 2 tablespoons olive oil\n\nFor the filling:\n- 250 g fresh spinach, cleaned\n- 250 g ricotta cheese\n- 50 g Parmesan cheese, grated\n- 1 egg\n- Nutmeg, salt and pepper to taste\n- 2 tablespoons pine nuts (optional)\n\nFor the sauce:\n- 3 tablespoons butter\n- 12 sage leaves\n- Salt and pepper to taste\n\nInstructions:\n1. Make pasta dough: combine flour, eggs, salt and olive oil. Knead until smooth and elastic.\n2. Wrap in plastic wrap and rest for 30 minutes.\n3. Cook spinach until wilted, squeeze dry, chop finely.\n4. Mix ricotta, spinach, Parmesan, egg, nutmeg, salt and pepper.\n5. Roll pasta thin on floured surface.\n6. Cut circles with cutter, fill center, fold and seal edges.\n7. Bring pot of salted water to boil.\n8. Cook ravioli until they float, then 2 minutes more.\n9. Melt butter in pan with sage leaves.\n10. Toss ravioli with butter, sage, salt and pepper.\n11. Serve immediately with extra Parmesan.\n","numLines":36,"startLine":1,"totalLines":36}}}
