{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01MX78Jei4ajVqSZLX8iavaX","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive picture. Let me analyze each pattern and propose solutions.\n\nKey observations:\n\n1. **Pattern A (7 failures)**: Section headers like `VEGETABLE SIDES                         145` — these have trailing page numbers separated by multiple spaces. Need a filter: if a line ends with `\\s{3,}\\d+$`, skip it.\n\n2. **Pattern B (10 failures)**: OCR garbling — these are evaluation harness issues, not extractor issues. The fix is in `titles_match` to add OCR-tolerant character normalization.\n\n3. **Pattern C (10 failures)**: Wrong position — the extractor picks \"SERVING SUGGESTION:\", \"GLAZE:\", etc. \n\nLooking at the actual failures, I see these are section labels that belong in `SECTION_LABELS`. Some are already there like \"serving\", but I'm missing exact matches for variations like \"serving suggestion\", \"serving suggestions\", \"for the sauce\", \"for the filling\". The Spinach and Ricotta Ravioli case shows \"For the sauce:\" being extracted as a title when it should be filtered. I need to expand the section labels list to catch these header patterns more comprehensively.\n\nBut there's something odd happening with the embedding scoring — for Oscypek Smażony, the actual title \"Oscypek Smażony\" is right at the top, yet the extractor is returning \"SERVING SUGGESTIONS:\" instead. That suggests the embedding model is scoring the wrong text higher, which means either my section label filtering isn't working or the similarity scoring is fundamentally off.\n\nLooking at the Spinach and Ricotta case more carefully, the title \"SPINACH AND RICOTTA RAVIOLI\" is clearly on line 3 in all caps, but the extractor returns \"For the sauce:\" from line 19. That's a huge gap, and it makes me think the issue is that sub-section labels like \"for the sauce,\" \"for the filling,\" and \"for the pasta dough\" aren't being caught by my current `isSectionLabel` filter, which only matches things like \"instructions.\"\n\nThe real problems are emerging: Pattern C is missing several section labels entirely — \"serving suggestion,\" \"serving suggestions,\" \"serving,\" \"glaze,\" and these \"for the...\" variants — plus for recipes like Grilled Halibut and Kopytka, the title appears far down in the file after garbage from the previous recipe. For Pattern D, I'm seeing that Kompot Porzeczkowy has metadata on lines 2-3 and the actual title on line 5, but the extractor is returning something unexpected.\n\nLooking at the other Pattern D examples, Lentil Vegetable Soup has its title on line 3 with a category tag in square brackets on line 5 — those bracketed lines need filtering. And for Chleb Żytni, the title is right on line 1, though the feedback mentions \"Porcji: 4\" being extracted, which suggests the layout might differ in the actual generated file. I'm noticing there are two versions of the Chleb Żytni file, and the feedback description doesn't quite match what I'm seeing in the .21 version I examined. Rather than getting caught up in individual discrepancies, I should focus on identifying the systemic patterns that need fixing across all the files. Looking at Pattern A, I need to add a filter to catch section headers with page numbers—specifically lines with text followed by multiple spaces and a page number at the end.\n\nFor Pattern B, the OCR garbling issues require character normalization in the evaluation harness itself, mapping common OCR mistakes like 0 to O, 1 to I or l, and various other character confusions. Pattern C needs additional section labels like \"serving suggestion,\" \"glaze,\" and some Polish terms, plus a filter for \"For the...\" style sub-headers, and special handling for files that start with leftover text from a previous recipe.\n\nNow looking at Pattern D and E — I need to handle metadata that appears before the title, like bracket tags and \"Porcji:\" patterns. For the case normalization issue, I'm checking whether `titles_match` already handles the comparison correctly since it normalizes both sides to lowercase, so `MINESTRONE SOUP` and `Minestrone Soup` should already match despite the case difference.\n\nBut the feedback says the extractor found the right line but returned raw all-caps text, so there's still something off with how the title is being processed or returned. I'm realizing the actual file structure might have the INGREDIENTS section appearing before the title line, which would be unusual. If that's the case, the position-based scoring would rank it lower, and another candidate might win instead. But the feedback indicates the extractor did find the correct line—it's just returning it in all caps rather than the expected title case.\n\nLooking at the `titles_match` function, it normalizes both the extracted and expected text to lowercase and handles separators, so case shouldn't matter. `MINESTRONE SOUP` and `Minestrone Soup` would both normalize to the same string and should match. So either the feedback is pointing to something else, or there's a mismatch I'm not seeing yet.\n\nLet me trace through the Sernik example more carefully. The file has OCR corruption with `ı` instead of `i` and `1` instead of `l`, but the extracted title is `SERNIK` and expected is `Sernik`. After normalization both should become `sernik`, so this should pass the match. Unless the extracted value isn't actually `SERNIK` as shown in the feedback. nik\" in \"sernık\"` → False because `ı` ≠ `i`. The `_strip_diacritics` function only handles Polish diacritics (ąćęłńóśźż), not Turkish dotless ı, so the comparison fails. But the feedback claims the extractor returns `SERNIK` in all caps, which doesn't appear anywhere in the file — there's `Sernık` on line 1 (with the corrupted Turkish character) and `Sernik` embedded in a sentence on line 34. I'm wondering if Pattern E might be getting misanalyzed here.\n\nActually, looking at `titles_match` again: it does lowercase both strings and strips diacritics, so `SERNIK` and `Sernik` should both normalize to `sernik` and match. That means Pattern E shouldn't actually be failing based on the logic. The feedback says it is though, so either the evaluation is case-sensitive somewhere else, or the feedback has miscategorized some of these failures.\n\nEither way, I should focus on what I can actually fix rather than getting stuck on whether Pattern E is real. Let me outline the concrete changes I need to make: add a page number suffix filter to reject lines with excessive whitespace followed by digits, implement OCR-tolerant matching to handle common character substitutions like 0/O and 1/I, and detect missing section labels by looking for prologue patterns.\n\nI also need to filter out metadata in brackets, add more section keywords like \"serving\" and \"instrukcje\", and handle the case where multiple ALL_CAPS lines with few words each should be treated as a single title. The caps coalescence logic should already handle cases like \"BARSZCZ UKRAIŃSKI\" where each word is short enough.\n\nLet me trace through why only \"UKRAIŃSKI\" is being extracted — the coalescence checks are passing for both lines, so something else might be filtering out \"BARSZCZ\" before it reaches the candidate stage. `BARSZCZ` alone is also a valid candidate, and after coalescence both `BARSZCZ UKRAIŃSKI` (coalesced) and `UKRAIŃSKI` (if it somehow enters as a separate candidate) compete. But after coalescence, the loop advances past both lines, so `UKRAIŃSKI` shouldn't be a separate candidate.\n\nWait, I need to trace through the code more carefully. The coalescence starts at `burstEnd` and iterates through `nonEmptyLines[burstEnd:]`. If line 1 is `BARSZCZ` and line 2 is `UKRAIŃSKI`, and they meet the criteria, they get coalesced into `BARSZCZ UKRAIŃSKI` and `ci` jumps to 3. So `UKRAIŃSKI` should NOT appear as a standalone candidate.\n\nBut what if the `burstEnd` detection is wrong? What if `BARSZCZ` is in the burst? `findBurstEnd` checks if text length is under 20 characters and passes the garbled check. `BARSZCZ` has 8 letters with only one vowel (\"A\"), giving a ratio of about 14%, which falls below the 15% threshold. Polish consonant clusters like \"sz\" and \"cz\" naturally create these low vowel ratios, so the garbled detector flags it. This means `BARSZCZ` gets filtered out as part of the burst.\n\nThe real issue is that the vowel ratio threshold of 0.15 is too strict for Polish words with heavy consonant clustering. I should either lower that threshold or add language-specific handling for Polish. I'm seeing that ALL_CAPS lines like \"BARSZCZ\" are being incorrectly flagged as garbled because they have very few vowels—only 1 out of 7 characters, which falls below the 15% threshold. The issue is that intentionally styled headings shouldn't be treated the same way as potential OCR noise. I could lower the vowel threshold, but a better approach might be to exempt ALL_CAPS text from burst detection entirely since it's clearly deliberate formatting.\n\nFor the subtitle preference issue, I'm noticing that when we have a short, properly-cased title candidate like \"Karp Pieczony\" at position 0 alongside a longer English description at position 1, the embedding similarity might favor the longer, more descriptive line. I should add logic to prefer position 0 when it has the characteristics of a clean title—short, 2-4 words, proper casing—even if the longer description scores higher on semantic similarity.\n\nLooking at the bigger picture, the core problem is that the algorithm relies too heavily on layered heuristics and embeddings aren't reliably separating titles from section headers. The patterns reveal that filtering is incomplete—many section labels and metadata patterns slip through—and the garbled detection is catching false positives like intentional styling.\n\nThe position signal gets